From a69c1d06df901714b5fe9e0f2188b133562eef74 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Nadia Chambers <nadia.yvette.chambers@ik.me>
Date: Wed, 29 Apr 2026 07:27:43 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 075/174] microblaze: fix THREAD_SIZE_ORDER vs THREAD_SIZE
 mismatch with PGCL

The microblaze stack allocator uses THREAD_SIZE_ORDER PAGE_SIZE pages,
but THREAD_SIZE is the mask used by current_thread_info() to find
thread_info from any stack pointer.  These two must agree, or the
mask returns a stale boundary that is not the start of the stack
allocation.

Without PGCL: PAGE_SIZE = 4KB, THREAD_SIZE_ORDER = 1, so 8KB
allocation, and THREAD_SIZE = 8KB matches.

With PGCL (PAGE_MMUSHIFT > 0): PAGE_SIZE = 64KB, THREAD_SIZE_ORDER = 1,
so 128KB allocation; the hardcoded 8KB THREAD_SIZE then gives a mask
that lands well above the actual thread_info, returning a pointer to
random pre-thread_info memory.  do_notify_resume() and other code
that reads current_thread_info()->flags then reads garbage and
diverges into unintended kernel paths (often a kernel page fault and
panic).

Switch microblaze to PAGE_SIZE-based stack when PGCL is on:
THREAD_SHIFT = PAGE_SHIFT, THREAD_SIZE = PAGE_SIZE, allocation
order 0 (one PAGE).  The traditional 8KB-out-of-two-4KB-pages stack
remains the default without PGCL.

Also un-#if-0 the diagnostic pr_warn in full_exception() so kernel-
mode exceptions are always logged with type/FSR/PC/ESR.  This was
gated behind #if 0 historically but is invaluable for debugging
exception storms (especially before console init, where it lands
in the printk ring buffer for inspection).

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7 <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
 arch/microblaze/include/asm/thread_info.h | 21 ++++++++++++++++++++-
 arch/microblaze/kernel/exceptions.c       |  2 --
 2 files changed, 20 insertions(+), 3 deletions(-)

diff --git a/arch/microblaze/include/asm/thread_info.h b/arch/microblaze/include/asm/thread_info.h
index 0153f7c2717c..5e326eae05c2 100644
--- a/arch/microblaze/include/asm/thread_info.h
+++ b/arch/microblaze/include/asm/thread_info.h
@@ -8,10 +8,29 @@
 
 #ifdef __KERNEL__
 
-/* we have 8k stack */
+#include <vdso/page.h>
+
+/*
+ * Thread stack is allocated as (1 << THREAD_SIZE_ORDER) PAGE_SIZE pages,
+ * but THREAD_SIZE is the mask used to find thread_info from any stack
+ * pointer.  These must agree, otherwise current_thread_info() returns
+ * a stale boundary that is not the start of the allocation.
+ *
+ * For PGCL kernels (PAGE_MMUSHIFT > 0) PAGE_SIZE is larger than the
+ * MMUPAGE, and a single PAGE already exceeds the 8K stack we want.
+ * Use PAGE_SIZE for both so the mask matches the allocation; the small
+ * waste is harmless on a 128MB target.  Without PGCL keep the
+ * traditional 8K stack out of two 4K pages.
+ */
+#if PAGE_MMUSHIFT > 0
+#define THREAD_SHIFT		PAGE_SHIFT
+#define THREAD_SIZE		PAGE_SIZE
+#define THREAD_SIZE_ORDER	0
+#else
 #define THREAD_SHIFT		13
 #define THREAD_SIZE		(1 << THREAD_SHIFT)
 #define THREAD_SIZE_ORDER	1
+#endif
 
 #ifndef __ASSEMBLER__
 # include <linux/types.h>
diff --git a/arch/microblaze/kernel/exceptions.c b/arch/microblaze/kernel/exceptions.c
index fd153d5fab98..032752c4dbab 100644
--- a/arch/microblaze/kernel/exceptions.c
+++ b/arch/microblaze/kernel/exceptions.c
@@ -71,11 +71,9 @@ asmlinkage void full_exception(struct pt_regs *regs, unsigned int type,
 {
 	addr = regs->pc;
 
-#if 0
 	pr_warn("Exception %02x in %s mode, FSR=%08x PC=%08x ESR=%08x\n",
 			type, user_mode(regs) ? "user" : "kernel", fsr,
 			(unsigned int) regs->pc, (unsigned int) regs->esr);
-#endif
 
 	switch (type & 0x1F) {
 	case MICROBLAZE_ILL_OPCODE_EXCEPTION:
-- 
